```troff
.TH fluxc 1 "August 15, 2024" "fluxc 1.0.0" "OpenCLAW Command Reference"
.SH NAME
fluxc \- FLUX constraint compiler for formally verified machine code
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B fluxc
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
\fIINPUT.guard\fR
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B fluxc
compiles FLUX guard constraint specification files (identified by the .guard file extension) into provably correct, target-specific machine code or hardware binaries.
This tool supports multiple backend targets, formal correctness verification via the Coq proof assistant, performance benchmarking, worst-case execution time (WCET) analysis, and stack safety hardening.
If no output file is specified via \fB-o\fR, fluxc will write the compiled binary to \fIINPUT\fR with the .guard suffix removed, appended with a target-specific extension (e.g., .x86_64 for x86-64 targets).
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B -o \fIOUTPUT\fR
Write the final compiled output to the file path specified by \fIOUTPUT\fR, overriding the default output location.
.TP
.B --target \fITARGET\fR
Specify the compilation target platform. Valid \fITARGET\fR values are:
.RS
.PD 0
.TP x86-64
64-bit x86 (AMD/Intel) desktop/server architecture
.TP arm
32-bit ARMv7-A and 64-bit AArch64 ARM architectures
.TP riscv
64-bit RISC-V GC extension architecture
.TP cuda
NVIDIA CUDA GPU device kernels
.TP fpga
Synthesizable FPGA hardware bitstreams
.TP wasm
WebAssembly bytecode
.PD
.RE
If this option is omitted, the default target is \fIx86-64\fR, or the value of the \fBFLUXC_TARGET\fR environment variable if set.
.TP
.B --verify
Run formal correctness verification using the Coq proof assistant to validate that the compiled code exactly matches the original guard specification. Exits with a non-zero status code if verification fails, and skips code generation unless verification succeeds.
.TP
.B --benchmark
Enable benchmarking mode. Prints compilation time, generated code throughput, and peak resource utilization metrics to standard output.
.TP
.B --wcet
Calculate a worst-case execution time estimate for the compiled constraint code using target-specific timing models. The WCET estimate is printed to standard output alongside the compiled binary.
.TP
.B --safe-tops-w
Enable safe top-of-stack watermarking for stack-based target architectures. This compile-time hardening pass tracks stack pointer bounds to prevent stack overflow vulnerabilities by inserting runtime bounds checks where necessary.
.TP
.B -h, --help
Display a summary of available command-line options and usage information, then exit immediately.
.TP
.B --version
Print version and licensing information for the fluxc compiler, then exit immediately.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic Compilation
Compile a guard specification to x86-64 machine code, writing the output to \fImy_guard.x86_64\fR:
.EX
fluxc --target x86-64 -o my_guard.x86_64 my_proof.guard
.EE
.SS Formal Verification
Compile a network security guard specification to RISC-V machine code and run Coq verification to ensure compliance with the original constraint rules:
.EX
fluxc --target riscv --verify network_policy.guard
.EE
If verification passes, the output binary will be written to \fInetwork_policy\fR by default.
.SS Benchmarking and WCET Analysis
Compile a sensor filtering guard to WebAssembly, enable performance benchmarking, and generate a worst-case execution time report:
.EX
fluxc --target wasm --benchmark --wcet sensor_filter.guard -o sensor_filter.wasm
.EE
.SS FPGA Hardware Compilation
Compile a motor controller guard specification for synthesis on an FPGA, with stack safety hardening enabled to prevent stack overflow attacks:
.EX
fluxc --target fpga --safe-tops-w motor_controller.guard -o motor_controller.bit
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
coq(1), gcc(1), clang(1), wasm-ld(1),
The full OpenCLAW project documentation: \%https://openclaw.org/docs/
.SH AUTHOR
Written by the OpenCLAW Formal Verification Team.
.SH BUGS
Report bugs via the GitHub issue tracker at \%https://github.com/openclaw/fluxc/issues
or by email to \%bugs@openclaw.org.
